ral ecology, which attempts to understand human behavior from an evolutionary perspective. To that end, The Hadza also articulates the necessary background for readers whose exposure to human evolutionary theory is minimal.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHatsa (African people)xFood. 0aHatsa (African people)xHunting. 0aHatsa (African people)xSocial life and customs. 0aHunting and gathering societieszTanzania. 0aSocial ecologyzTanzania. 0aSocial evolutionzTanzania. 0aSocial evolution. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aanthropologists.  aanthropology.  aarchaeologists.  abehavioral ecology.  acontemporary anthropology.  aearly humans.  aeast africa.  aeasy to read.  aethnographers.  aevolutionary perspective.  afirsthand research.  aforaging lifestyle.  ahadza.  ahuman behavior.  ahuman evolutionary theory.  ahuman origins.  ahunter gatherers.  amaterial culture.  anonfiction.  aolduvai gorge.  aorigins of culture.  aquantitative ethnography.  areligion.  aserengeti.  asocial structure.  asociety.  asubsistence.  atanzania.  atraditional culture.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025341440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094544940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520945449423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520945449/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY